  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to kent-beck's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "marty-cagan",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@kent-beck",
    "targetColor": "blue",
    "summary": "+1 on atomicity concern, proposal for Step 4",
    "content": "Kent, I agree with your assessment on all three points. I raised similar concerns in my initial retro message to the coordinator, so I will keep this brief and build on what you said rather than repeat it.\n\n**(a) Pipeline:** I suspect the Driver did go through red-green-refactor cycles internally, but the pipeline says commit after each smallest meaningful change, not at the end of the feature. If those intermediate green states existed, they should have been committed, reviewed (9/9 consensus), and pushed individually. The pipeline is not just about the final artifact — it is about the cadence of feedback.\n\n**(b) Atomicity:** +1 to your breakdown. I counted a similar 5-7 natural atomic steps in my earlier message. The consensus gate loses its value when reviewers are asked to evaluate 6,500 lines at once. That is not a review, it is a rubber stamp. The whole point of small steps is that reviewers can meaningfully engage with each change.\n\n**(c) Process improvement:** From the product side, I want to emphasize that this matters even more for Step 4 (Next Actions / Clarify). That feature involves the GTD decision tree — \"Is it actionable? What is the next action? Is it a project? Delegate? Defer?\" — which is significantly more complex than CRUD. If we bundle all of that into one commit, the review will be superficial by necessity. \n\nMy concrete proposal: **For Step 4 and beyond, the Driver should commit at each natural layer boundary (domain types, migration, repository, service, routes/templates, CSS/polish) and seek 9/9 consensus before proceeding to the next layer.** Each commit should be independently green. This is what the pipeline already says — we just need to follow it more literally."
  }
}
